labels.name: product-feedback
labels.description: Indicating it's product feedback

items.body:
If a new environment was created after 10 June 2020 using SDK 1.7.0 or lower, training on local compute or an Azure Databricks customer may fail with the above error due to an update in the py-cpuinfo package. (Environments created on or before 10 June 2020 are unaffected, as well as experiments run on remote compute as cached training images are used.) To work around this issue, either of the two following steps can be taken:

1. Update the SDK version to 1.8.0 or higher (this will also downgrade py-cpuinfo to 5.0.0):
```bash
pip install --upgrade azureml-sdk[automl]
```

2. Downgrade the installed version of py-cpuinfo to 5.0.0:
```bash
pip install py-cpuinfo==5.0.0
```

items.title: Creation of FileDataset and conversion to FileDataset result in different behaviours
items.body:
Hi folks, 

Not sure if this is simply a documentation issue or an SDK level problem, but I notice that creation of a FileDataset using `Dataset.File.from_files`, and conversion of a TabularDataset to a FileDataset using `to_csv_files(separator=',')` - though they both result in a FileDataset object - cause different behaviours.

This came up when trying to mount these as named inputs to a PythonScriptStep. 

The former method (`Dataset.File.from_files`) enables us to mount the FileDataset in such a way that the path(s) to file(s) are accessible via the environment variables of the script receiving the input. If the "Dataset" is represented by one file (e.g. CSV or Parquet), using `input_path = os.environ['file_dataset_input_name']` will result in `input_path` being populated by a full path to the file in question, so we can load it easily using, for instance, pandas.read_csv().

However, casting a TabularDataset created from the same source file to a FileDataset using `to_csv_files(separator=',')` as documented here, and mounting this as a named input, results in `input_path` being populated only by the directory enclosing the file, meaning we can't load the files in the receiving script. 

I tried appending the known original filename to this to see if that made the difference, but it seems the original filenames may not be maintained when mounting (attempts to read the data from the file like this were unsuccessful), so we need the full path(s) every time.

It would be nice if it was either made consistent in the SDK that a FileDataset object always mounts in a predictable fashion, or if the difference is important, that it is documented, probably under the likes of to_csv_files(), before someone tries to use it.

items.title: Explain default behavior for 'Early Stopping' and 'Stopping Criteria'

labels.name: assigned-to-author
labels.description: Assigned the issue to the listed article author.

items.body:
In the current reference page this is the only info about 'Early Stopping':
enable_early_stopping bool
Flag to enable early termination if the score is not improving in the short term.

Customers are demanding additional details about AutoML 'Stopping Criteria' and  'Early Stopping'. The following default behavior needs to be added to this page (probably at the 'enable_early_stopping' param section):

Default Behavior for Stopping Criteria: 
- If iteration and experiment timeout not specified -> we turn early stopping on, experiment_timeout = 6 days, num_iterations = 1000 
- If experiment timeout specified: early_stopping = off, num_iterations = 1000 
 
Early Stopping Logic: 

- No early stopping for first 20 iterations (landmarks) 
- Early stopping window starts on 21st iteration and looks for early_stopping_n_iters iterations (currently set to 10) 
This means that the first iteration where stopping is probably the 31st. 
 
- AutoML still schedules 2 ensemble iterations AFTER early stopping, which might result in higher scores 
 
- Early stopping is triggered if the absolute value of best score calculated is same for past early_stopping_n_iters iterations. I.e., if there is no improvement in score for early_stopping_n_iters iterations. 

If this info is too large for a parameter's section, we might want to put it as a 'Default Behavior for Stopping Criteria' at the end of the page, within the REMARKS section?

Right now the description of the parameter is just this (check above in this page):

max_cores_per_iteration
